    "text": "Oh, thanks for tagging me, <@UFBQNBYER>!\n\nI spent a lot of time studying Alexander and still can't quite say I know how it all applies to software, but it's important to know that software Design Patterns as popularized by the Gang of Four while inspired by Alexander’s work ultimately doubled down on the wrong aspects (reusability). That was never what Alexander intended. That doesn't take away from the significance of their work, just means they got inspired but went somewhere else with that momentum.\n\nAlexander was more about the generative nature of (ambiguous human) language that allows people to only specify to a degree needed and leave details open for adaptation to a specific context. It's hardly possible to convey in a single paragraph what that exactly means. \n\nA good introduction to Alexander is this one from Ryan Singer: <https://www.ryansinger.co/christopher-alexander-a-primer/|https://www.ryansinger.co/christopher-alexander-a-primer/>\n\n_Patterns of Software_ (as mentioned by <@UCUSW7WVD>) by Richard P. Gabriel is probably the best attempt to draw connections between software and Alexander’s work. RPG is also who talked me into writing a paper about Simplicity, which is what the linked presentation above is about.",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "thread_ts": "1765483599.000789",
    "parent_user_id": "U04E5QAD6DD",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "type": "rich_text",
        "block_id": "4yamD",
        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "rich_text_section",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Oh, thanks for tagging me, "
              },
              {
                "type": "user",
                "user_id": "UFBQNBYER"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "!\n\nI spent a lot of time studying Alexander and still can't quite say I know how it all applies to software, but it's important to know that software Design Patterns as popularized by the Gang of Four while inspired by Alexander’s work ultimately doubled down on the wrong aspects (reusability). That was never what Alexander intended. "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "That doesn't take away from the significance of their work, just means they got inspired but went somewhere else with that momentum"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "."
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "\n\nAlexander was more about the generative nature of (ambiguous human) language that allows people to only specify to a degree needed and leave details open for adaptation to a specific context. It's hardly possible to convey in a single paragraph what that exactly means. "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "\n\n"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "A good introduction "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "to Alexander "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "is this one from Ryan Singer: "
              },
              {
                "type": "link",
                "url": "https://www.ryansinger.co/christopher-alexander-a-primer/",
                "text": "https://www.ryansinger.co/christopher-alexander-a-primer/"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "\n\n"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Patterns of Software",
                "style": {
                  "bold": false,
                  "italic": true
                }
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " (as mentioned by "
              },
              {
                "type": "user",
                "user_id": "UCUSW7WVD"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": ") by "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Richard P. Gabriel is probably the best attempt to draw connections between software and Alexander"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "’s "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "work"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "."
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " RPG is also who talked me into writing a paper about Simplicity, which is what the linked presentation above is about"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
